WEBVTT

00:00.195 --> 00:01.862
<i>Previously on "Better Call Saul..."</i>

00:02.633 --> 00:04.094
Clifford Main hired jimmy.

00:04.182 --> 00:05.081
He had his doubts.

00:05.229 --> 00:07.495
Truth be told, Kim Wexler pushed for this.

00:07.823 --> 00:09.039
You faked evidence.

00:09.124 --> 00:11.158
Mmm, I think you're splitting hairs.

00:11.260 --> 00:13.594
Why would you risk the
best job you've ever had

00:13.679 --> 00:15.462
for some pro-bono case?

00:15.547 --> 00:17.764
I was hoping, maybe,
you could do me a favor.

00:17.866 --> 00:19.766
Anything you need, I'll be there.

00:19.852 --> 00:21.468
You still in touch with your people?

00:21.553 --> 00:23.470
Depends on the type of
work you're looking for.

00:23.555 --> 00:24.771
You tell me what you got.

00:24.857 --> 00:25.973
I'll tell you what I'll do.

00:26.058 --> 00:26.974
Why are you here?

00:28.010 --> 00:29.992
To bear witness.

00:31.000 --> 00:37.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:14.306 --> 01:16.340
Sorry about the hiccup, folks.
It won't be long.

01:28.570 --> 01:29.936
You got five minutes.

01:34.743 --> 01:37.110
Howdy, folks.

01:37.162 --> 01:40.781
Could someone tell me
if Mrs. Alma May Urbano

01:40.783 --> 01:41.915
is on board?

01:41.950 --> 01:43.333
Alma May Urbano.

01:44.586 --> 01:47.120
There you are. Hello, dear.

01:47.122 --> 01:49.289
Very good to meet you.

01:49.341 --> 01:50.340
My name's Jimmy.

01:50.376 --> 01:51.858
I tried to visit you at Sandpiper,

01:51.894 --> 01:53.927
but they wouldn't allow me to.

01:53.962 --> 01:55.379
Hey, you know what?

01:55.431 --> 01:56.630
It doesn't matter.

01:56.632 --> 01:59.299
I saw your bus broken down, here you are.

01:59.449 --> 02:00.648
Lucky me.

02:00.700 --> 02:03.401
Do you prefer to be called Mrs. Urbano

02:03.453 --> 02:05.737
or Alma May or just plain Alma?

02:05.789 --> 02:09.407
My last name is McGill,
but you can call me Jimmy.

02:09.459 --> 02:11.075
Hey, everyone! My name's Jimmy McGill.

02:11.128 --> 02:14.746
I'm an attorney at law,
but, uh, don't mind me.

02:14.798 --> 02:17.248
Just talk amongst yourselves.

02:17.250 --> 02:18.750
Now, Alma May,

02:18.752 --> 02:21.719
do you recall responding to a mailer

02:21.755 --> 02:25.924
from my law firm, Davis & Main,
of Santa Fe, New Mexico?

02:25.976 --> 02:27.308
I... I don't know.

02:27.344 --> 02:31.179
Well, we were looking to help
any Sandpiper residents

02:31.231 --> 02:33.565
who may have been overcharged

02:33.600 --> 02:36.234
for, uh, basic goods and services.

02:36.269 --> 02:37.519
Now, does that ring a bell?

02:37.571 --> 02:40.772
Oh! Maybe. Was it yellow?

02:40.824 --> 02:41.990
It's canary yellow.

02:42.025 --> 02:43.825
I picked that color myself.

02:45.328 --> 02:48.112
Well, ma'am, I'm here to make
sure you get your money back.

02:48.165 --> 02:50.198
What are you talking about?

02:50.250 --> 02:51.499
Who took Alma May's money?

02:51.535 --> 02:54.169
Uh, well, now, that's a very good question.

02:54.204 --> 02:56.671
And thank you for asking, mister, uh...?

02:56.706 --> 02:58.873
Amos... Amos Lydecker.

02:58.925 --> 03:01.426
Mr. Lydecker, Jimmy McGill.

03:01.461 --> 03:04.712
Now, nobody took
anybody's money, uh, exactly.

03:04.764 --> 03:05.964
Okay?

03:05.966 --> 03:08.600
It's not like the Sandpiper
people, you know,

03:08.635 --> 03:11.603
put on a ski mask and, uh...

03:11.638 --> 03:15.273
mugged Alma May here at gunpoint.

03:15.308 --> 03:18.059
So I want you to put that mental
image right out of your head.

03:18.111 --> 03:19.777
See, what we're talking about
here is more of a...

03:19.813 --> 03:21.279
it's just a discrepancy.

03:21.314 --> 03:22.947
It's... it's a little thing.

03:22.983 --> 03:25.149
It's... it's fairly innocent.

03:25.151 --> 03:26.951
But we need to fix it.

03:26.987 --> 03:28.236
Do you follow me?

03:29.990 --> 03:31.489
Well, put it this way.

03:31.491 --> 03:35.126
Alma May, let's say you're out
on a date with your boyfriend.

03:35.161 --> 03:37.078
You do have a boyfriend, right?

03:37.130 --> 03:38.746
Ah! You don't?

03:38.798 --> 03:39.881
Come on. You...

03:39.916 --> 03:42.166
Alma May's holding out on me.

03:43.169 --> 03:44.802
Do you have a nephew?

03:44.838 --> 03:47.338
Nephew? Oh, y-yes... Steve.

03:47.390 --> 03:48.556
Okay, Steve.

03:48.592 --> 03:51.175
- Is he a good guy?
- Yeah, very good.

03:51.177 --> 03:52.343
Okay.

03:52.395 --> 03:54.395
So, let's say you and Steve go out to dinner

03:54.431 --> 03:56.147
at, uh... well, Birdie's.

03:56.182 --> 03:58.850
That's where you're all headed today, right?

03:58.852 --> 04:00.735
All right.

04:00.770 --> 04:03.021
So, both of you have a great meal.

04:03.073 --> 04:05.690
It's chicken-fried steak and green beans,

04:05.692 --> 04:07.091
and it's all perfect.

04:07.127 --> 04:09.160
Here comes the check.

04:09.195 --> 04:11.362
"Hey, wait a doggone..."

04:11.364 --> 04:14.916
24 bucks for a side of buttermilk biscuits?

04:14.951 --> 04:17.084
"That doesn't sound right, now, does it?"

04:17.120 --> 04:18.586
No, it does not.

04:18.622 --> 04:21.505
It sounds like something got added up wrong.

04:21.541 --> 04:24.342
Well, naturally, you send your nephew Steve

04:24.377 --> 04:26.110
to talk to the manager,

04:26.146 --> 04:28.930
and naturally, the manager
corrects the mistake.

04:28.965 --> 04:31.299
And what's more, he gives you a coupon

04:31.351 --> 04:33.635
for a free meal next time you come in.

04:33.687 --> 04:34.636
How about that?

04:34.688 --> 04:36.104
Good.

04:36.139 --> 04:40.892
Well, same kind of thing is what
happened at Sandpiper Crossing.

04:42.646 --> 04:47.065
And nothing makes me sadder

04:47.067 --> 04:50.401
than to see people
of the Greatest Generation...

04:50.403 --> 04:53.571
people like my own Nana and Bobo...

04:53.573 --> 04:57.742
gettin' overcharged
by some great, big company...

04:57.744 --> 04:59.827
even if it was an accident.

05:00.997 --> 05:04.082
Now, I know that the
good people at Sandpiper

05:04.084 --> 05:08.252
want to make this right sooner
or later, but you know what?

05:08.254 --> 05:12.256
Well, sometimes, it's just easier

05:12.258 --> 05:17.929
if you get your nephew Steve
to go take care of it for you.

05:17.931 --> 05:22.600
And that's how I want you to think of me.

05:22.652 --> 05:24.769
Georgiana.

05:24.771 --> 05:26.270
Hey, there, Georgie girl. Thank you.

05:26.272 --> 05:28.356
Oh, it's all there, everything I need.

05:28.408 --> 05:31.159
Thank you so much. Enjoy your lunch.

05:31.194 --> 05:33.027
Alma May, you did it.

05:33.079 --> 05:35.413
Thank you so much. Thank you.

05:35.448 --> 05:37.865
Thank you, Henry.

05:37.917 --> 05:39.250
All right.

05:39.285 --> 05:41.369
Hey, Sue. Okay.

05:41.421 --> 05:43.755
Beautiful penmanship.

05:43.790 --> 05:45.123
A lost art.

05:53.557 --> 05:56.364
Synced and corrected by oykubuyuk
www.addic7ed.com

06:00.396 --> 06:02.463
Schweikart and Cokely are
pursuing an aggressive strategy,

06:02.499 --> 06:03.965
but looking at the relevant case law,

06:04.000 --> 06:06.985
I don't think it's going to
play with this magistrate judge.

06:07.037 --> 06:09.120
I read over a dozen of her rulings,

06:09.155 --> 06:12.573
all of which have sided with the
plaintiff on cases like this.

06:12.626 --> 06:15.810
I've included a memo to that
effect in today's materials,

06:15.845 --> 06:17.879
which you can peruse at your leisure.

06:17.914 --> 06:19.180
Thanks, Erin.

06:19.215 --> 06:23.184
How about we move on to client outreach?

06:25.889 --> 06:27.822
Jimmy?

06:27.857 --> 06:28.806
You still with us?

06:28.842 --> 06:30.258
Uh...

06:30.260 --> 06:32.343
I'm gonna save you from having to brag.

06:32.395 --> 06:34.095
Over 200 new Sandpiper clients

06:34.097 --> 06:35.930
signed over the past three weeks.

06:35.982 --> 06:37.098
Well-done, Jimmy.

06:37.100 --> 06:38.599
Thank you. Thanks, Cliff.

06:38.601 --> 06:40.018
Uh, right now,

06:40.070 --> 06:43.664
we're in the process of mapping
out the entire southwest,

06:43.866 --> 06:47.268
targeting the largest
Sandpiper facilities first.

06:47.351 --> 06:50.936
Phoenix, Colorado Springs,
Fort Worth, Provo...

06:50.988 --> 06:52.455
that's just for starters.

06:52.502 --> 06:56.170
Ideally, my goal... another 200
by the end of the month.

06:56.222 --> 06:58.406
With this many folks,
we have an excellent shot

06:58.441 --> 07:00.308
at a solid batch of plaintiffs

07:00.343 --> 07:02.343
for the classes in each district.

07:02.395 --> 07:03.428
Excellent.

07:03.480 --> 07:05.763
Look forward to the next report.

07:05.815 --> 07:09.016
On to a stickier wicket...
coordinating actions.

07:09.069 --> 07:10.151
I'm sorry.

07:10.186 --> 07:12.570
Before we move on, I'd like to go back

07:12.605 --> 07:15.189
to client outreach just for a moment.

07:15.241 --> 07:17.275
Looking over these numbers here,

07:17.327 --> 07:20.194
really, astonishing results, Jimmy.

07:20.196 --> 07:21.245
Incredible.

07:21.281 --> 07:23.614
Your last trip to Amarillo,

07:23.666 --> 07:26.451
you came back with 22 new clients.

07:26.503 --> 07:28.703
- 24.
- 24.

07:28.755 --> 07:30.004
I'm confused.

07:30.039 --> 07:31.773
Um, how many people out there

07:31.808 --> 07:35.209
actually responded to our direct mailer?

07:35.261 --> 07:37.044
One.

07:37.097 --> 07:39.480
Oh. Right. Yeah.

07:39.516 --> 07:42.733
A Mrs. Alma May Urbano.

07:42.769 --> 07:49.624
But you got 24 new clients
from this one response?

07:49.659 --> 07:53.561
That is... [Chuckles] Wow.

07:53.596 --> 07:54.829
Well, you're welcome.

07:54.864 --> 07:56.631
I mean, what? Is there a problem?

07:56.666 --> 07:58.866
Well, uh, might not some parties...

07:58.918 --> 08:01.202
the opposing counsel, for example...

08:01.254 --> 08:03.454
see this differential and conclude

08:03.506 --> 08:06.624
that there may have been
some solicitation involved?

08:06.676 --> 08:08.342
I did not solicit.

08:08.378 --> 08:10.344
I'm just wondering how
you account for your success.

08:10.380 --> 08:11.963
Because it will definitely raise eyebrows

08:12.015 --> 08:14.348
over at Schweikart & Cokely.

08:14.384 --> 08:16.434
I'm sorry, but it will.

08:16.469 --> 08:19.687
Particularly in a case involving seniors,

08:19.722 --> 08:23.357
for whom the ethical
guidelines on solicitation

08:23.393 --> 08:26.144
were virtually created by the ABA.

08:26.196 --> 08:28.980
Chuck, I'm sure that...

08:30.066 --> 08:32.732
Jimmy, if you could clear this up,

08:32.784 --> 08:34.467
that would be helpful.

08:34.504 --> 08:38.039
I went to Amarillo to confer with a client

08:38.073 --> 08:42.443
and to make sure that we had
a solid, good-faith basis

08:42.477 --> 08:45.046
for our case there, overall.

08:45.081 --> 08:46.881
And as many of you are aware,

08:46.916 --> 08:49.817
I've visited more than my share
of retirement homes.

08:49.853 --> 08:51.636
These are close-knit communities.

08:51.671 --> 08:53.971
Let me tell you, word gets around real fast.

08:54.007 --> 08:57.091
If Dorothy in Phase Two
gets a new Rascal Scooter,

08:57.093 --> 08:58.593
well, it's big news.

08:58.645 --> 09:01.679
So these other 23 residents,
they approached you.

09:01.731 --> 09:03.314
Cliff, they heard the scuttlebutt

09:03.349 --> 09:05.399
before I crossed state lines.

09:05.435 --> 09:08.903
And I certainly didn't have to
go knocking on any doors.

09:08.938 --> 09:12.023
And is it any surprise
that they want to speak

09:12.075 --> 09:13.741
with the guy who was there to show them

09:13.776 --> 09:15.343
they may have money coming their way?

09:15.378 --> 09:18.663
I gotta tell you, with all that in mind,

09:18.698 --> 09:20.915
I should've done better.

09:22.085 --> 09:24.869
Makes sense. Howard?

09:25.955 --> 09:28.189
Chuck?

09:28.224 --> 09:30.157
We good to move on?

09:32.712 --> 09:34.679
And, Chuck, not incidentally,

09:34.714 --> 09:36.097
it is absolutely vital

09:36.132 --> 09:38.432
that we dot our I's and cross our T's here.

09:38.468 --> 09:39.433
Invaluable.

09:39.469 --> 09:41.636
So, thank you.

09:41.688 --> 09:43.804
The price of excellence
is eternal vigilance.

09:43.806 --> 09:46.807
Indeed.

09:46.809 --> 09:47.975
Coordination.

09:47.977 --> 09:49.944
I believe that's where we left off.

09:49.979 --> 09:51.145
That's right.

09:51.197 --> 09:53.564
Brian, this is your thing,
so why don't you take this?

09:53.616 --> 09:54.982
Sure.

09:55.034 --> 09:57.735
Considering the dimensions of these cases,

09:57.787 --> 09:59.654
taken together and individually,

09:59.706 --> 10:01.739
it makes sense to designate someone

10:01.791 --> 10:03.157
to handle the scheduling.

10:03.159 --> 10:06.210
What I'm proposing is that
we create a small team at D&M

10:06.246 --> 10:08.963
dedicated specifically
to coordinating all elements

10:08.998 --> 10:10.498
of the individual actions.

10:10.500 --> 10:13.000
- We'll loop in HHM on anything...
- Uh, Brian, I'm sorry.

10:13.052 --> 10:14.835
Excuse me for interrupting.

10:14.837 --> 10:17.972
Uh, I just want to say
that I take Chuck's point.

10:18.007 --> 10:19.340
I do.

10:19.342 --> 10:23.177
I mean, this is, like,
a wife-of-Caesar type of thing.

10:23.179 --> 10:26.681
There can't even be a hint of solicitation.

10:26.733 --> 10:28.849
So I'm gonna pull back.

10:28.901 --> 10:31.185
All right, no more meet-and-greets

10:31.187 --> 10:33.154
at the Sandpiper facilities.

10:33.189 --> 10:35.156
I'll find another way to proceed.

10:35.191 --> 10:37.792
Well, Jimmy, we'll leave that up to you.

10:37.827 --> 10:40.361
You know, client outreach
is your department.

10:40.413 --> 10:43.030
Uh, where was I?

10:43.082 --> 10:44.865
Okay, right.

10:44.867 --> 10:47.668
If we have a more consolidated
nerve center here in New Mexico,

10:47.704 --> 10:48.669
where the...

10:56.045 --> 10:57.545
Hey, Kim, uh, where can I get a copy

10:57.547 --> 10:58.846
of that Neiderman deposition?

10:58.881 --> 11:00.298
I've got an extra Neiderman, Jimmy.

11:00.350 --> 11:01.766
You can have one of mine.

11:01.801 --> 11:03.100
Oh, wow. Thanks, Erin.

11:03.136 --> 11:04.218
Yeah, no worries.

11:05.722 --> 11:07.555
Shoot. Where'd I put that?

11:07.557 --> 11:10.224
Thanks, that's...

11:12.061 --> 11:15.112
Man, do you believe Chuck in there?

11:15.148 --> 11:16.897
Jesus. Solicitation?

11:16.899 --> 11:18.733
Let me tell you, when we
were building this case,

11:18.735 --> 11:21.569
I was chasing down 80-year-old mall walkers.

11:21.621 --> 11:23.237
That was solicitation.

11:23.239 --> 11:24.739
But did he say "boo"?

11:24.741 --> 11:26.624
Bullshit he did.

11:26.659 --> 11:28.292
What happened in Texas?

11:28.328 --> 11:29.960
Nothing.

11:29.996 --> 11:32.313
I did my job.

11:32.348 --> 11:33.998
You didn't do a song and dance in
the dayroom for the old-timers?

11:34.050 --> 11:35.666
No. No.

11:35.718 --> 11:38.836
Not... not in the dayroom.

11:38.888 --> 11:41.339
Jimmy, you know solicitation
can get you disbarred.

11:41.391 --> 11:42.340
This matters.

11:42.392 --> 11:43.924
Well, here's what I think matters...

11:43.976 --> 11:46.093
24 senior citizens now have representation.

11:46.145 --> 11:47.428
Before I went,

11:47.480 --> 11:49.397
they didn't even know
they were getting ripped off.

11:49.432 --> 11:51.015
Now they have us in their corner.

11:51.067 --> 11:52.767
How is that not a win?

11:52.769 --> 11:55.569
You said in there you'd find another way.

11:55.605 --> 11:57.438
Did you mean it?

11:57.440 --> 12:00.191
Sure. Absolutely. I...

12:05.748 --> 12:07.081
Look, I...

12:08.918 --> 12:11.869
I need you to understand
something very critical here.

12:11.921 --> 12:13.120
Shoot.

12:14.674 --> 12:17.658
I put myself on the line
to get you this job.

12:18.728 --> 12:20.010
Uh, okay.

12:20.046 --> 12:22.797
I thought it was 'cause
I'm sensational with old people.

12:22.849 --> 12:25.516
Yeah, and who do you think told them that?

12:25.551 --> 12:27.635
So, what... you threw me a bone?

12:27.687 --> 12:29.270
No... asshole.

12:29.305 --> 12:32.390
You know I believe in you.

12:33.976 --> 12:36.143
But then I made my beliefs known to them.

12:36.195 --> 12:38.863
And now everything you do
reflects back on me with Howard,

12:38.898 --> 12:40.698
'cause ultimately, I talked him into

12:40.733 --> 12:42.867
going out on a limb for you, too.

12:44.203 --> 12:45.486
Do you understand?

12:45.538 --> 12:48.789
It's... it's... it's my word,
it's my judgment.

12:48.825 --> 12:49.824
Yeah.

12:54.714 --> 12:58.416
You and I both know you can do this job.

13:03.306 --> 13:05.890
But please, you just have to do it right.

13:16.352 --> 13:19.153
Well... you want to make sure

13:19.188 --> 13:23.991
you put in the batteries
the right way or he won't work.

13:24.026 --> 13:26.360
Then you close them up.

13:26.412 --> 13:27.578
And...

13:27.613 --> 13:32.283
I think... I think
you're good to go, young lady.

13:32.335 --> 13:36.337
Why don't you give his foot a squeeze?

13:40.126 --> 13:43.177
He's funny!

13:43.212 --> 13:44.879
Oh, darlin'.

13:46.549 --> 13:51.552
I think I'll name you... Mr. Snuggles.

13:53.055 --> 13:54.355
Are you hungry?

13:54.390 --> 13:57.308
I'm gonna get you some mashed potatoes.

13:57.360 --> 14:00.027
That should get you through to next month.

14:01.230 --> 14:02.530
Mike, thank you.

14:02.565 --> 14:05.199
But you shouldn't feel that you need to...

14:05.234 --> 14:06.567
Too late.

14:12.241 --> 14:13.741
Something up?

14:13.743 --> 14:15.042
Mm.

14:15.077 --> 14:17.378
Feels like something's up.

14:17.413 --> 14:18.712
No, it's...

14:18.748 --> 14:20.464
I didn't get much sleep.

14:20.500 --> 14:22.216
My head's... I'm sorry.

14:22.251 --> 14:25.419
You tell me it's none of
my business, I'll drop it.

14:25.471 --> 14:27.338
I don't want you to worry.

14:27.390 --> 14:29.990
Not the worrying kind.

14:33.229 --> 14:35.796
Last two nights, I heard gunshots.

14:35.831 --> 14:39.166
First night, they were
maybe a block or two over

14:39.202 --> 14:40.201
and woke me up.

14:40.236 --> 14:41.902
My first thought was firecrackers,

14:41.938 --> 14:43.938
and that's what I assumed at the time,

14:43.990 --> 14:46.407
but then last night...
there's no mistaking it.

14:46.442 --> 14:47.825
There was three of them.

14:47.860 --> 14:50.110
They were quick... pop, pop, pop... closer.

14:50.112 --> 14:51.278
It was...

14:51.330 --> 14:53.364
Like they were right outside the house.

14:53.416 --> 14:54.365
You call the cops?

14:54.417 --> 14:55.749
Yeah.

14:55.785 --> 14:57.418
Took them over an hour to get here,

14:57.453 --> 14:59.537
then they looked around
for a whole two minutes,

14:59.589 --> 15:01.755
but by then, of course,
there was nothing to see.

15:03.292 --> 15:05.342
I'm staying here tonight.

15:05.378 --> 15:06.594
No, Mike, no.

15:06.629 --> 15:07.928
That's not necessary.

15:07.964 --> 15:09.630
No, it is not a problem.

15:09.682 --> 15:10.965
I'll take the couch.

15:11.017 --> 15:13.934
Mike, you asked, so... I answered.

15:13.970 --> 15:17.221
Please don't make me sorry I told you.

15:22.883 --> 15:25.234
Kaylee, come, hmm?

15:25.296 --> 15:27.463
Get your supper.

15:42.995 --> 15:45.946
